  <p>You walk into the lounge room and there's a distinct smell of smoke — but the fire hasn't been lit for days, or even weeks. It might be a faint background smell, or strong enough that guests notice it when they walk in. Either way, it shouldn't be there, and it won't go away on its own.</p>

  <p>A fireplace that smells like smoke or burning when it's not in use is one of the most common chimney-related complaints we get in Melbourne, particularly as the weather starts to cool and heaters that have sat idle all summer suddenly get switched on again. Here's what causes it and what fixes it.</p>

  <h2>Why Does a Fireplace Smell When It's Not Being Used?</h2>

  <p>The smell is almost always coming from one of two sources: creosote and soot buildup inside the flue, or air movement through the chimney carrying that smell into the room. Understanding which one is causing the problem tells you how to fix it.</p>

  <h3>Creosote and Soot Buildup</h3>

  <p>Every fire leaves behind creosote — a tar-like residue that coats the inner walls of the flue. Over a season of use, that buildup can be substantial. Creosote has a strong, acrid, smoky smell that intensifies in warm or humid conditions. On a warm summer day, or after rain, the smell can become noticeably stronger as the creosote softens slightly and off-gasses into the flue. If the chimney has any downward air movement — which it often does when the heater isn't in use — that smell gets drawn into the room.</p>

  <p>If your fireplace smells mainly in warm weather, after rain, or when it's humid, creosote smell from an uncleaned flue is almost certainly the cause.</p>

  <h3>Downdraught — Air Coming Down the Chimney</h3>

  <p>When the heater isn't running, the flue is just an open column connecting your living room to the outside. Air can move through it in either direction depending on pressure differences. In many Melbourne homes — particularly well-sealed modern houses with exhaust fans running — the indoor air pressure is slightly lower than outside, which draws outside air down through the chimney. That air picks up the smell of soot and creosote as it passes through the flue, and delivers it directly into the room.</p>

  <p>This is why some homeowners notice the chimney smell is worse when the rangehood or bathroom exhaust fan is running. Those fans pull air out of the house, increase the pressure differential, and pull more air — and smell — down the chimney.</p>

  <h3>A Blocked Flue or Bird Nest</h3>

  <p>A partial blockage — from a bird nest, accumulated debris, or a fallen piece of flue liner — traps stale air and moisture inside the flue. That trapped air gets warm and stagnant, and the smell of old soot, damp, and sometimes decomposing nesting material seeps into the room. If the smell has a musty or organic quality alongside the smokiness, a blockage is likely involved.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p>A blocked flue isn't just a smell problem. A partial blockage can prevent combustion gases — including carbon monoxide — from venting properly when you do light the fire. If you suspect a blockage, don't use the heater until it's been inspected and cleared.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Rain and Moisture in the Flue</h3>

  <p>Water and creosote combine to produce a particularly sharp, unpleasant smell — somewhere between smoke and something chemical. If you notice the smell is strongest after heavy rain or in wet weather, moisture getting into the flue is mixing with soot deposits and amplifying the odour. This can indicate a damaged or missing chimney cap, cracked flue crown, or deteriorating mortar around the chimney top that's allowing water entry.</p>

  <h2>Why Is the Smell Worse in Summer?</h2>

  <p>This is one of the most common questions. The heater hasn't been used for months — why does it smell now? Two reasons:</p>

  <p>First, heat. Warm air rises, which means in summer the air naturally moves downward through the chimney (from the cool interior toward the warmer outside at ground level — but the thermal pattern through the flue reverses compared to winter). That downward movement carries flue odours into the room more readily than in winter when the heater is running and draw is upward.</p>

  <p>Second, temperature activates creosote. The tar compounds in creosote soften and volatilise more readily in warm conditions. A flue that smelled fine in winter can become noticeably smelly through the warmer months as the accumulated creosote sits there and slowly off-gasses.</p>

