  <h2>Does Burning Candles or Air Freshener Help?</h2>

  <p>No. It masks the smell temporarily but does nothing about the source. The creosote is still there, the downdraught is still happening, and the smell will keep coming back. The only thing that eliminates a creosote smell is removing the creosote — which means a professional clean.</p>

  <p>Some homeowners try closing the damper (if their fireplace has one) to reduce downdraught. This helps with airflow, but the smell can still penetrate through gaps around the damper plate if the creosote buildup is significant. And if the damper is already in poor condition, it may not seal properly at all.</p>

  <h2>What Actually Fixes a Smelly Chimney</h2>

  <p><strong>Professional chimney clean.</strong> This is the fix for the vast majority of cases. The clean removes the creosote and soot that's producing the smell, clears any blockages that are trapping stale air, and allows the professional to check for structural issues (cracked crown, damaged cap) that might be letting water in. Most homeowners notice an immediate difference — the smell is gone or dramatically reduced after the clean.</p>

  <p><strong>Chimney cap or cowl.</strong> If there's no cap on the chimney top, or the existing one is damaged, fitting a proper cap reduces both downdraught and water ingress. A good cap significantly reduces how much outside air (and the smell it carries back through a dirty flue) enters the home.</p>

  <p><strong>Addressing negative air pressure.</strong> If the smell is worst when exhaust fans are running, a small permanent air supply vent near the heater helps equalise pressure and reduce downdraught through the flue. This is particularly relevant in newer, well-sealed Melbourne homes.</p>

  <h2>Is a Chimney Smell a Health Risk?</h2>

  <p>The smell itself isn't immediately dangerous, but what causes it can be. Creosote is a known carcinogen with sustained exposure. More importantly, a flue that's driving smell into your living space — especially through downdraught — can also allow combustion gases including carbon monoxide to enter the room when the heater is in use. Carbon monoxide has no smell and no colour, and won't be detected without a dedicated CO detector.</p>

  <p>If you don't have a carbon monoxide detector in the room with your heater, get one before the next time you light it. They cost around $40–60 at most hardware stores and could save a life.</p>

  <h2>When to Book a Clean</h2>

  <p>If your fireplace or wood heater is producing a smoke smell when it's not in use, the timing is actually good news: you've identified the problem before winter, which means you can get it cleaned now and have it ready to use properly when the cold weather arrives. Melbourne winters start to bite from late May — booking a clean in April or early May means you're ahead of the rush and you're not dealing with the smell through summer.</p>

